properties.DEFAULT_EXPERIMENT.EXPERIMENTAL_DESCRIPT: we soak the adhesive joint aluminum sheets in 3w% NaCl into a 5L bottle at 70°C for 48h. The bottle cap is connected with a reflux tube on the top. In the winter, the bottle is covered by a cloth to maintain the temperature.
properties.DEFAULT_EXPERIMENT.EXPERIMENTAL_GOALS: aluminum surface treatment is necessary to increase the stability of adhesive joint aluminum. By the aging test, we can study which kind of phosphonic acid molecular structure can increase the aging/corrosion resistance at the epoxy/aluminum interface.

projects.description: In this project, we systematically compare the influence of different organophosphonic acid structures on the adhesion/durability of epoxy adhesive joint aluminum alloy 5754 sheets. The tensile shear test is used to compare the adhesion strength and the durability of the epoxy adhesive joint phosphonic acid-modified aluminum sheets. XPS is used to characterize the phosphonic acid-modified aluminum surface.

In this work steric and electronic (resonance and inductive) effect of series of phosphonic acid's molecular structure on its interaction with aluminum/aluminum oxide surface has been studied. To understand the dynamic processes of species transfer on the aluminum surface, electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) and inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectrometry (ICP-OES) investigations are performed. In addition, the modified aluminum oxide surface is characterized for the phosphorus concertation and the aluminum oxide thickness by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) and time of flight secondary ion mass spectroscopy (ToF-SIMS) respectively.

properties.QUALITY_CONTROL: If the samples surfaces are not clean enough, it can be seen in the eSFA measurement
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Sample handling is carried out in laminar-flow cabinet (Heraeus Instruments, HPH 12/65, Empa Inv.-Nr. 34352) in order to prevent particle contamination of mica. The air in the cabinet is taken through a HEPA filter and is blown in very smooth, laminar flow towards the user guarantying almost clean room conditions in the cabinet. All accessories which are needed for cleavage of mica are carefully cleaned with ethanol. Gloves which are needed for preparation of mica are washed in water, dry-purged with the nitrogen gun and afterwards clean with ethanol. It is recommended to wear a face mask during the whole cleaving process in order to minimize the aerosol contamination risk of the mica surface.

 

2. The performance of the HEPA filter and so the number of particles inside the laminar-flow can be checked by ABACUS 301 Particle Measuring Systems Inc. (Serial No. 5462, ETHZ No.1819805). After checking, ensure that no other items are in front of mica during cleaving, which reduces accidental contamination risk.

3. For the preparation of the samples surface and the backing sheet flats of mica with high optical   quality are used. The initial thickness of the mica blocks is around 0.2 - 0.5 mm. Using strong scissors, cut out a backing sheet into a rectangle of approx. 10 x 10 cm. Cut one edge off in order to mark the orientation. For that, use the template which is placed in the laminar-flow cabinet. Cleave one side of the backing sheet – the surface should not exhibit any steps, scratches or wrinkles. The backing sheet is used as long-term storage for cleaved mica, whereas the adhering faces are protected from any contamination. Note that no clean cleaved surface should come into contact with cabinet's surface.  Copy the backing sheet form and each mica sample positions into the lab notebook book. Label the backing sheet (name & date) on the back (i.e. not clean cleaved side).

 

 

4. Place two strips of approx. 1.5 cm wide Teflon film horizontally on the top and bottom of the backing sheet (it is possible to place only one Teflon film in the middle if only few samples are need). Attach the Teflon band on the back of the backing sheet with tape. The Teflon strip is important in order to create a non-adhesive border for the mica samples to facilitate lift-off. Note that the small portions of mica, which overlap with the Teflon band are protected by the backing sheet and thus not usable spots for the eSFA measurement.

5.Prepare your working space for the correct cleaving. Place a semi-circular row of glass beakers in front of you to intermediately store cleaved mica blocks (i.e. beaker rim cleaned by ethanol and mica clean side up). Leave a central gap in the semi-circle where you place the cleaving and cutting tools, clean downwind. Make sure that there is a clean and constant laminar flow through the areas where the glasses are placed (no other items should be placed before the glasses, since they may spontaneously release adsorbed surface particles - see Fig. 4).

6. Use sharp-pointed tweezers to successively cleave the mica sheet into thinner sheets. This procedure needs to be repeated until the sheets can be teared by hand. Check the mica surface homogeneity by holding the sample into the light. With some experience, it is possible to distinguish between high quality areas for further cleaving. As a next step, the thin sheets are further torn by hand – this should result in delamination of thin mica samples of thickness below 10 μm. Sections which are thin enough in order to perform eSFA measurements can be recognized by strong interference color which appears when the sample is hold into white light (blue, pink, green). Yellow shining pieces are usually >5 μm thick. Note that it is extremely important to not have any scratches or particles on the mica sample surface. The cleaved surface cannot come to contact either with the laminar-cabinet surface or with any other items and should remain in clean laminar flow at all times.

 

7.Once a homogenous region of at least 2 cm x 2 cm is extracted (it is suitable size in order to cut out at least two samples of 1 cm x 1 cm), the sample can be temporarly fixed on metal blocks for cutting. It is important to keep in mind the optical orientation of the mica crystal in order to avoid double peaks from birefringence. Since the relative orientation angle of exactly 90° of the mica sample is needed, the first cut along the 2x2 cm piece can serve as a reference of the main cutting orientation of the mica. One should lay down all cut pieces in the same reference orientation onto the backing sheet and/or possibly note the orientation in a lab journal.

 

 

8.The cutting is performed using surgical scissors which were fixed at home-built x-y-z-translation stage. Important: Do not touch the sample surface with any kind of accessories. Cutting should be performed downstream (i.e. cutting particles are carried away) in the laminar flow in order to keep the samples surface as clean as possible.

9.Cut at least two samples (1cm x 1cm each) from the same step-free piece of thin mica to obtain the same thickness. Alternatively larger pieces of mica can be cut out and be placed onto the backing sheet – in this approach the samples will be cut after the silvering during the gluing of mica. 

10.Transfer individual samples with tweezers directly onto the backing sheet, with experiment surface down and partial overlap with the Teflon film on one edge. If the mica surface is clean, the sample will stick to the backing sheet via Van der Waals forces without forming any voids or wrinkles. It is important to write down the sample configuration on the backing sheet and all orientations in a suitable log book, in order to recognize which sample comes from which piece of mica sheet. We like to adopt the nomenclature "20220329 mica 2.4" for the mica piece nr. 4, cut out from mica sheet nr. 2 on March 29, 2022.

properties.INTRODUCTION: The standard substrate for eSFA measurements is (ruby) muscovite mica. Individual mica blocks can be cleaved into μm thin and atomically smooth sheets of several cm2 area. Two pieces of homogeneous and identical thickness of mica are used as model surface in the interferometric eSFA.
properties.PRINCIPLE: In summary, the cleaving process is a manual process using tweezers needles and scissors and requiring some manual skills. The operator is wearing gloves and is working inside a laminar flow cabinet. The cabinet air quality (no particles) is periodically (ca. all 3-6 months) measured using a laser light scattering particle counter. Filters are only exchanged if the air quality is no longer "class 0", i.e. not a single particle detected in 2 minutes aspiration time.

properties.QUALITY_CONTROL: In order to check the silver thickness, one spot can be placed on the backing sheet as a "dummy" sample. This specific sample can be removed directly after coating and measured by the profilometer.
properties.PROCEDURE:
In general, the procedure consits four different steps (conditioning, sample loading, evaporation, repressurization) which in following will be described in more detail.

 

Figure 3:  Mechanical pump under the table. The white arrow marks the valve which if referred follows as "valve under the table"

Conditioning

1. Before starting, the amount of silver in the tungsten boat needs to be checked. For this purpose, open the chamber. Check if the boat, located at the bottom of the chamber, consists sufficient amount of silver. If not, place carefully a plastic tube on the boat and refill the 

2. Optional pre-evacuation of the system is recommended (e.g. during mica cleaving) since it can reduce the time of pumping once the samples are loaded inside the chamber. 

3. In order to evacuate the chamber check if the valve on top of the chamber is closed and press `Belüftungsventil ZU`. Start the vaccum pumps - press "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement). Open the valve under the Turobotronik pump immediately after starting the pump. Press PM & and activate the HM. Wait until the pressure reach at least 10-2 mbar and press START the turbo pump on the Turbotronik device (accel. should go on and you can hear the sound). Run the pump for a while (3-12 h, depends on the previous usage).

 

Sample loading

4. Stop the Turbotronik pump and close the valve under the table. Make sure that the valve above (where the samples are inserted) is open. Switch off HV and go to TM2 display. Wait until the pressure drops till 100 mbar. Open the nitrogen valves at the wall and press Belüftungsventil ZU (the light should be off). Wait several minutes and put the sample in.

5. In order to evacuate the chamber, repeat the third step described under conditioning.  Check if the valve on top of the chamber is closed and press `Belüftungsventil ZU`. Start the vaccum pumps - press "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement). Open the valve under the Turobotronik pump immediately after starting the pump. Press PM & and activate the HM. Wait until the pressure reach at least 10-2 mbar and press START the turbo pump on the Turbotronik device (accel. should go on and you can hear the sound). Wait until the pressure reach around 10-6 before starting the evaporation. 

 

Evaporation

6. Make sure that the two cooling valves (at the wall near the eSFA) are open and that the shutter is closed. Press "Bedampfung/Kühlung"(evaporation/cooling) – the switch should light up. 

7. Start the deposition monitor INFICON. Note that the system shows the coating rate in Å/s (first value top left) and the thickness of the coating in Å (value at top right). 

8. Turn on the thermal evaporation power supply (switch main). Check the applied current (it should be around 50-70 A). The wheel in the middle of the device is used for increasing of the current. 

9. The coating is performed by melting of high-purity silver in a tungsten boat by resistive heating. For that increase the current continuously and slowly to 160 A using the wheel. Always keep a look at the pressure and the voltage – both values should remain stable (very slight changes are fine). From 160 A go up with 5 A-steps and wait several seconds (approx. 30 s) after each step. At a certain current the high-purity silver in the tungsten boat should start to melt. If this is observed, wait approx. 5-7 minutes.

10. In order to achieve a homogenous coating with low surface roughness, the deposition rate of 1 Å/s may be applied. Reset the deposition monitor (press open/close at the INFICON device). Open the valve which opens the shutter (below the vacuum chamber) and increase the current until you reach the deposition rate of 1 Å/s. If the deposition rate is stable, leave the system until it reach 0.400 Å. In order to stop the coating, close the valve under the chamber (shutter) manually. Go slowly down (wait several seconds after each step) with the current until the silver is not melting anymore. 

11. Afterwards, reduce the current slowly until it reach the minimum value (otherwise the tungsten boat may be destroyed). Note your coating parameters (origin pressure after pumping; max. pressure during evaporation; time of the evaporation; thickness of the evaporated layer; deposition rate) into the lab book. Switch off the thermal evaporation power supply (switch main).

Repressurization

12. Press "Bedampfung/Kühlung"(evaporation/cooling) – the switch light should go off. Turn off the cooling water valves. Close the valve under the pump and press Turbotronik "stop". Turn off HV and switch to the other sensor TM2. The pressure in the chamber will increase, wait several seconds until it reach 10-1 mbar.  Turn on the nitrogen valve at the wall (it can remain open during evaporation).  Press Belüftungsventil ZU (venting valve, closed when pressed) and ventil the chamber with nitrogen.  Take out your sample.

13. Once the sample is out, press "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement) in order to stop the mechanical pump. Open and close immediately the valve under the table in order to avoid oil in the chamber. Press Belüftungsventil ZU (venting valve, closed when pressed).

Usually all vacuum pumps need to be switched off (see step 13), however, for maintenance reasons, it is possible to run the mechanical vacuum pump for several hours in order to heat up the filter and remove all dirt from it. 

For further detailed information on the setup contact Urs Schütz, Empa St.Gallen.
properties.SCOPE:
The silvering setup consists of a vacuum chamber (ETH Inventar No. 1695243) with two-stage vacuum pumps, the turbomolecular pump (ETH Inventar No. 1680643) and the mechanical pre-vacuum pump (RZ 9 S/N: 35216302, 2011/10). Both pumps can reach a typical base pressure of 10^-6 mbar after some 2 hours. Furthermore, a high-vacuum and low-vacuum pressure gauge is needed in order to monitor the pressure over a wider range. The monitoring of the thickness is performed with a calibrated quartz crystal (QCM). Between the low-vacuum pressure gauge and adsorption trap, a valve is placed (Model No. CBV-75-SS-16, Serial No. 94-A-47-2385) which allows to run the pumps independently (in follows referred as "valve under the table").  The evaporation boat in the system is powered by high current transformer.

There are four main instruments used to monitor the conditions during the thermal silvering procedure. The black box at the upper level on a shelf is an operating box for the turbomolecular pump (Turbotronik NT 151/361). Next to the left is situated the QCM deposition monitor (INFICON deposition monitor XTM/2). Note that the device is not able to open the shutter automatically (even if the display would suggest so). The shutter must be open manually – the turning handle is placed under the vacuum chamber.  Above the deposition monitor, a pressure monitoring system (COMBIVAC CM31) is located. On a second, lower, shelf the thermal evaporation power supply (Kurt J. Lesker Company) is placed. The applied voltage and current are displayed in two red segment displays mounted in the table top. Furthermore, four switches are integrated in the table - "Adsorptionsfallenheizung" (adsorption trap heating), "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement), "Bedampfung/Kühlung"(evaporation/cooling), Belüftungsventil ZU (venting valve, closed when pressed).
properties.PRINCIPLE: The backing sheet with the mica samples is slid into a holder frame of the vacuum chamber vacuum lock. Use the thermal evaporation system to deposit a semi-transparent silver layer of QCM monitored thickness of 40 nm.

properties.INTRODUCTION: Once the backing sheet carries enough mica samples, a semi-transparent silver mirror is coated onto the exposed side of the sample in order to define the finesse of the thin-film interferometer inside the eSFA.

properties.NOTES: If chloroform is used, it is recommended to wear a face mask (e.g. FFP2 mask).
properties.QUALITY_CONTROL: An optimal thickness of the glue on the disk surface is around 10 μm – interference colors should be visible if the disk is held to reflect white light.
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Ensure that all accessories and spin coater (self-built) are cleaned with ethanol before starting the deposition of the chloroform-glue solution on disk surface. Connect the power supply to the spin coater and turn it on. The spin coater is powered by a power supply EA Triple Power Supply (No. EA-PS2316-050).

2. Before spinning, the disks are cleaned carefully with ethanol and optical paper. Use only a specific paper for cleaning (neoLab, order no. 1-7218) of the flat and cylindrical optical surfaces to prevent scratching.

3. Place the cleaned disc on the spin coater and apply few droplets of the glue (epoxy resin – check chemistry section) using a syringe. Make sure the surface be fully covered with glue before the spinning starts. Place splash blocker (e.g. plastic ring) around the sample and turn the spin coater on.

4. The layer thickness can be controlled by the speed of the spin coater and the effective viscosity/concentration of the solution. Find optimal speed setting (it can marked with the red arrow by position 10) in order to create a homogenous film of glue on the disk. Optimal spinning time should be around 2 minutes.

5. Once the coating is finished, ensure that the coating is homogenous and tick enough. An optimal thickness of the glue on the disk surface is 10 μm – interference colors should be visible if the disk is held to reflect white light. Clean the flat floor of the disc by wiping it over a solvent soaked optical paper. If the coating is accepted, the disk can be stored for final solvent evaporation in a petri dish and can be used for further sample preparation. If not, the disc can be moved to the chloroform solution in order to resolve the glue. The procedure should be carefully repeated for each disk.
properties.INTRODUCTION: In order to perform eSFA measurements with mica, the two mica samples are glued onto two cylindrically polished face of fused silica discs. For this reason discs with a diameter of 10 mm each serve as substrate for the mica samples and experimentally form the crossed cylinders with a radius of curvature of 20 mm.
properties.PRINCIPLE: Mica is glued onto the Si-disk using a UV curing polymer glue or thermoplastic resin (e.g. Exxon 1004F).
properties.EQUIPMENT_REAGENTS:
• spin coater (self-built)
  • power supply EA Triple Power Supply (No. EA-PS2316-050)
  • specific paper for cleaning (neoLab, order no. 1-7218)
  • Exxon 1004F, chloroform, ethanol
properties.HEALTH: check saftey regulations of chloroform (e.g. under S25248.pdf (fishersci.com))

properties.PROCEDURE:
1.Remove the tube from PTFE-air filter (Sartorius Midisart 2000) and open the valve slowly (Lenz, DIN NS 24/29). Wait until the pressure inside the desiccator has equilibrated. Before lifting the cover, move the desiccator to the laminar-flow cabinet in order to reduce the risk of particle contamination. Insert your backing sheet into a free slot of the sample holder (the valve remain open). Close the desiccator main seal and place it back to the table. Make sure that the Viton O-ring is placed correctly.

2. Evacuate the desiccator using the oil-free diaphragm pump (PFEIFFER Vacuum, Mod.Nr.PK T05 065).  Connect the tubing and after few minutes (>30 min) of pumping, close the valve and turn the pump off.
properties.INTRODUCTION: A backing sheet can carry multiple mica samples that are used for several consecutive experiments. The samples are thus stored, with the backing sheet, in a desiccator, which allows storage of a few weeks.
properties.EQUIPMENT_REAGENTS:
• desiccator
  • PTFE-air filter (Sartorius Midisart 2000)
  • valve (Lenz, DIN NS 24/29)
  • oil-free diaphragm pump (PFEIFFER Vacuum, Mod.Nr.PK T05 065)
  • rubber lines

properties.QUALITY_CONTROL: clean and flat mica surface in the middle of the sample (without wringels, scretches etc.)
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Prewarm the previously prepared disks at a temperature of 125° to slowly evaporate any remaining residual solvent gases.

2. The temperature is then increased to 135-140 °C. The temperature is controlled by Weller WSD81 soldering station.  If the glue on the silica discs starts to melt, single mica samples can be removed with sharp tweezers from the backing sheet. Note that in order to minimize any risk of contamination of the mica surface, wearing of a face mask is highly recommended.

3. Rotate the mica sample mirror side down by 180° in order to have the silver side facing the glue and put the mica sample carefully on the silica disc, remembering the orientation of the reference cut on the backing sheet. It is important to produce a smooth, unbuckled surface, if the Si cylinder axis is placed perpendicular to the laminar flow and the upwind edge of mica is lowered first. Don’t use pressure to glue the sample on the disc – instead try to establish contact between the upwind edge of the sample and then let the mica slowly settle down with a gentle push from the laminar flow. Reaching conformal contact with the silica disk can take a few minutes.

4.Remove the silica discs with the mica sample from the heat plate too cool off in a clean laminar flow. Put the samples into the eSFA as soon as possible to minimize the exposition to the ambient laboratory air.

properties.PROCEDURE:
In general, the procedure consits four different steps (conditioning, sample loading, evaporation, repressurization) which in following will be described in more detail.

 

Figure 3:  Mechanical pump under the table. The white arrow marks the valve which if referred follows as "valve under the table"

Conditioning

1. Before starting, the amount of silver in the tungsten boat needs to be checked. For this purpose, open the chamber. Check if the boat, located at the bottom of the chamber, consists sufficient amount of silver. If not, place carefully a plastic tube on the boat and refill the 

2. Optional pre-evacuation of the system is recommended (e.g. during mica cleaving) since it can reduce the time of pumping once the samples are loaded inside the chamber. 

3. In order to evacuate the chamber check if the valve on top of the chamber is closed and press `Belüftungsventil ZU`. Start the vaccum pumps - press "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement). Open the valve under the Turobotronik pump immediately after starting the pump. Press PM & and activate the HM. Wait until the pressure reach at least 10-2 mbar and press START the turbo pump on the Turbotronik device (accel. should go on and you can hear the sound). Run the pump for a while (3-12 h, depends on the previous usage).

 

Sample loading

4. Stop the Turbotronik pump and close the valve under the table. Make sure that the valve above (where the samples are inserted) is open. Switch off HV and go to TM2 display. Wait until the pressure drops till 100 mbar. Open the nitrogen valves at the wall and press Belüftungsventil ZU (the light should be off). Wait several minutes and put the sample in.

5. In order to evacuate the chamber, repeat the third step described under conditioning.  Check if the valve on top of the chamber is closed and press `Belüftungsventil ZU`. Start the vaccum pumps - press "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement). Open the valve under the Turobotronik pump immediately after starting the pump. Press PM & and activate the HM. Wait until the pressure reach at least 10-2 mbar and press START the turbo pump on the Turbotronik device (accel. should go on and you can hear the sound). Wait until the pressure reach around 10-6 before starting the evaporation. 

 

Evaporation

6. Make sure that the two cooling valves (at the wall near the eSFA) are open and that the shutter is closed. Press "Bedampfung/Kühlung"(evaporation/cooling) – the switch should light up. 

7. Start the deposition monitor INFICON. Note that the system shows the coating rate in Å/s (first value top left) and the thickness of the coating in Å (value at top right). 

8. Turn on the thermal evaporation power supply (switch main). Check the applied current (it should be around 50-70 A). The wheel in the middle of the device is used for increasing of the current. 

9. The coating is performed by melting of high-purity silver in a tungsten boat by resistive heating. For that increase the current continuously and slowly to 160 A using the wheel. Always keep a look at the pressure and the voltage – both values should remain stable (very slight changes are fine). From 160 A go up with 5 A-steps and wait several seconds (approx. 30 s) after each step. At a certain current the high-purity silver in the tungsten boat should start to melt. If this is observed, wait approx. 5-7 minutes.

10. In order to achieve a homogenous coating with low surface roughness, the deposition rate of 1 Å/s may be applied. Reset the deposition monitor (press open/close at the INFICON device). Open the valve which opens the shutter (below the vacuum chamber) and increase the current until you reach the deposition rate of 1 Å/s. If the deposition rate is stable, leave the system until it reach 0.400 Å. In order to stop the coating, close the valve under the chamber (shutter) manually. Go slowly down (wait several seconds after each step) with the current until the silver is not melting anymore. 

11. Afterwards, reduce the current slowly until it reach the minimum value (otherwise the tungsten boat may be destroyed). Note your coating parameters (origin pressure after pumping; max. pressure during evaporation; time of the evaporation; thickness of the evaporated layer; deposition rate) into the lab book. Switch off the thermal evaporation power supply (switch main).

Repressurization

12. Press "Bedampfung/Kühlung"(evaporation/cooling) – the switch light should go off. Turn off the cooling water valves. Close the valve under the pump and press Turbotronik "stop". Turn off HV and switch to the other sensor TM2. The pressure in the chamber will increase, wait several seconds until it reach 10-1 mbar.  Turn on the nitrogen valve at the wall (it can remain open during evaporation).  Press Belüftungsventil ZU (venting valve, closed when pressed) and ventil the chamber with nitrogen.  Take out your sample.

13. Once the sample is out, press "Vakuumpumpen/ Messung" (vaccum pumps/measurement) in order to stop the mechanical pump. Open and close immediately the valve under the table in order to avoid oil in the chamber. Press Belüftungsventil ZU (venting valve, closed when pressed).

Usually all vacuum pumps need to be switched off (see step 13), however, for maintenance reasons, it is possible to run the mechanical vacuum pump for several hours in order to heat up the filter and remove all dirt from it. 

For further detailed information on the setup contact Urs Schütz, Empa St.Gallen.

properties.INTRODUCTION: Once the backing sheet carries enough mica samples, a semi-transparent silver mirror is coated onto the exposed side of the sample in order to define the finesse of the thin-film interferometer inside the eSFA.

properties.QUALITY_CONTROL: If the samples surfaces are not clean enough, it can be seen in the eSFA measurement
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Sample handling is carried out in laminar-flow cabinet (Heraeus Instruments, HPH 12/65, Empa Inv.-Nr. 34352) in order to prevent particle contamination of mica. The air in the cabinet is taken through a HEPA filter and is blown in very smooth, laminar flow towards the user guarantying almost clean room conditions in the cabinet. All accessories which are needed for cleavage of mica are carefully cleaned with ethanol. Gloves which are needed for preparation of mica are washed in water, dry-purged with the nitrogen gun and afterwards clean with ethanol. It is recommended to wear a face mask during the whole cleaving process in order to minimize the aerosol contamination risk of the mica surface.

 

2. The performance of the HEPA filter and so the number of particles inside the laminar-flow can be checked by ABACUS 301 Particle Measuring Systems Inc. (Serial No. 5462, ETHZ No.1819805). After checking, ensure that no other items are in front of mica during cleaving, which reduces accidental contamination risk.

3. For the preparation of the samples surface and the backing sheet flats of mica with high optical   quality are used. The initial thickness of the mica blocks is around 0.2 - 0.5 mm. Using strong scissors, cut out a backing sheet into a rectangle of approx. 10 x 10 cm. Cut one edge off in order to mark the orientation. For that, use the template which is placed in the laminar-flow cabinet. Cleave one side of the backing sheet – the surface should not exhibit any steps, scratches or wrinkles. The backing sheet is used as long-term storage for cleaved mica, whereas the adhering faces are protected from any contamination. Note that no clean cleaved surface should come into contact with cabinet's surface.  Copy the backing sheet form and each mica sample positions into the lab notebook book. Label the backing sheet (name & date) on the back (i.e. not clean cleaved side).

 

 

4. Place two strips of approx. 1.5 cm wide Teflon film horizontally on the top and bottom of the backing sheet (it is possible to place only one Teflon film in the middle if only few samples are need). Attach the Teflon band on the back of the backing sheet with tape. The Teflon strip is important in order to create a non-adhesive border for the mica samples to facilitate lift-off. Note that the small portions of mica, which overlap with the Teflon band are protected by the backing sheet and thus not usable spots for the eSFA measurement.

5.Prepare your working space for the correct cleaving. Place a semi-circular row of glass beakers in front of you to intermediately store cleaved mica blocks (i.e. beaker rim cleaned by ethanol and mica clean side up). Leave a central gap in the semi-circle where you place the cleaving and cutting tools, clean downwind. Make sure that there is a clean and constant laminar flow through the areas where the glasses are placed (no other items should be placed before the glasses, since they may spontaneously release adsorbed surface particles - see Fig. 4).

6. Use sharp-pointed tweezers to successively cleave the mica sheet into thinner sheets. This procedure needs to be repeated until the sheets can be teared by hand. Check the mica surface homogeneity by holding the sample into the light. With some experience, it is possible to distinguish between high quality areas for further cleaving. As a next step, the thin sheets are further torn by hand – this should result in delamination of thin mica samples of thickness below 10 μm. Sections which are thin enough in order to perform eSFA measurements can be recognized by strong interference color which appears when the sample is hold into white light (blue, pink, green). Yellow shining pieces are usually >5 μm thick. Note that it is extremely important to not have any scratches or particles on the mica sample surface. The cleaved surface cannot come to contact either with the laminar-cabinet surface or with any other items and should remain in clean laminar flow at all times.

 

7.Once a homogenous region of at least 2 cm x 2 cm is extracted (it is suitable size in order to cut out at least two samples of 1 cm x 1 cm), the sample can be temporarly fixed on metal blocks for cutting. It is important to keep in mind the optical orientation of the mica crystal in order to avoid double peaks from birefringence. Since the relative orientation angle of exactly 90° of the mica sample is needed, the first cut along the 2x2 cm piece can serve as a reference of the main cutting orientation of the mica. One should lay down all cut pieces in the same reference orientation onto the backing sheet and/or possibly note the orientation in a lab journal.

 

 

8.The cutting is performed using surgical scissors which were fixed at home-built x-y-z-translation stage. Important: Do not touch the sample surface with any kind of accessories. Cutting should be performed downstream (i.e. cutting particles are carried away) in the laminar flow in order to keep the samples surface as clean as possible.

9.Cut at least two samples (1cm x 1cm each) from the same step-free piece of thin mica to obtain the same thickness. Alternatively larger pieces of mica can be cut out and be placed onto the backing sheet – in this approach the samples will be cut after the silvering during the gluing of mica. 

10.Transfer individual samples with tweezers directly onto the backing sheet, with experiment surface down and partial overlap with the Teflon film on one edge. If the mica surface is clean, the sample will stick to the backing sheet via Van der Waals forces without forming any voids or wrinkles. It is important to write down the sample configuration on the backing sheet and all orientations in a suitable log book, in order to recognize which sample comes from which piece of mica sheet. We like to adopt the nomenclature "20220329 mica 2.4" for the mica piece nr. 4, cut out from mica sheet nr. 2 on March 29, 2022.

[1] Frantz, P. and M. Salmeron, Preparation of mica surfaces for enhanced resolution and cleanliness in the suface forces apparatus. Tribology Letters, 1998. 5(2-3): p. 151- 153

[2] Perkin, S., et al., Forces between mica surfaces, prepared in different ways, across aqueous and nonaqueous liquids confined to molecularly thin films. Langmuir, 2006. 22(14): p. 6142-6152 

[3] Tobias E. Balmer, Resolving structural and dynamical properties in nano-confined fluids, Diss., Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule Zürich, Nr. 17359, 2007
properties.INTRODUCTION: The standard substrate for eSFA measurements is (ruby) muscovite mica. Individual mica blocks can be cleaved into μm thin and atomically smooth sheets of several cm2 area. Two pieces of homogeneous and identical thickness of mica are used as model surface in the interferometric eSFA.
properties.PRINCIPLE: In summary, the cleaving process is a manual process using tweezers needles and scissors and requiring some manual skills. The operator is wearing gloves and is working inside a laminar flow cabinet. The cabinet air quality (no particles) is periodically (ca. all 3-6 months) measured using a laser light scattering particle counter. Filters are only exchanged if the air quality is no longer "class 0", i.e. not a single particle detected in 2 minutes aspiration time.

properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Make sure that intern water supply circle is on (Legrand (UV2) MD01 120F1) and turn on the cooling water flows using the valves at the wall, behind the eSFA table. Doublecheck if the water is flowing by looking at  "water wheels" behind the eSFA.

 

 

Figure 2: eSFA setup at Empa St. Gallen (April 2022) with major components needed for starting the eSFA

 

2. Start the power supply of the arc lamp, Müller Elektronik Optik Type SVX1450, by pressing "NETZ", the red light "START" will come on to indicate sufficient cooling water flow. Then switch on the xenon arc lamp by pressing the red button "START".

3. Turn on the temperature power supply and the temperature controller. Switch on the PCI unit and start the power strip at the table. You should now hear the spectrometer initialization sounds (variation in grating position).

4. Turn on the PC. Log-in into the account (402, Labor Ruby - password protected) and start the following programs placed on the desktop: 440_Temperature & 510_CCD.
properties.PRINCIPLE:
Common sample surfaces are 2-10 µm thick, manually cleaved mica substrates (see MICASOP01 - cutting & cleaving) with nominally 40 nm-thick evaporated silver layer on the outer faces (see SOP_mica_preperation_silvering). By moving the motor by the amount M, the distance D between the surfaces can be varied. One of the surface is mounted on a compliant spring with spring constant k. During the experiment, the distance D as a function of the actuator is optically measured (using Multiple Beam Interferometry), thus allowing to calculate the sum surface force, F=k(M-D).

The traditionally used SFAs are based on the acquisition of a single fringe wavelength, thus resulting in a distance resolution of ≈100-300 pm [1]. Considering the acquisition of multiple fringe wavelengths and the evaluation for interference spectra using spectral correlation interferometry, the precision of distance measurement can be around 20 pm. Based on this improvements, the instrument is called then extended surface forces apparatus (eSFA).
properties.EQUIPMENT_REAGENTS:
Figure 1: Schematic of the eSFA setup.

The extended Surface Force Apparatus (eSFA) consists of an automated version of the SFA3TM (1997, Surforce, USA). The instrument is placed in an own-build insulated enclosure, providing stable thermal conditions ±20mK after a few hours equilibration. The temperature is controlled by EUROTHERM 2216e controller, powered by external power supply EA-PS-7032-10 A. Several encoded DC motors are inside the enclosure in order to make optical adjustments of the setup and changing the distance between the two surfaces. The movement of the motors is controlled by a PMC controller card inside an EXSYS EX-1031 4x PCI Expansion Box. The motors are individually connected to a separate pinout box via D-sub connectors.

The light is provided by a Xenon Short arc lamp with 450 W (SN: EQRKF i548), powered by xenon lamp power supply Müller Elektronik Optik Type SVX1450. The white light is directed into the eSFA housing via two dichroic mirrors in series; this minimizes the IR heating of the experiment. The outcoming light is collected by imaging lens and directed into the spectrograph (Acton Research Corporation Spectra Pro-500i, 0.5 Meter Triple Grating Monochromator), where the spectra are detected by a high-resolution CCD camera Allied Vision Technologies (GigE 4000, 4008x2672 pixels).  The spectrometer contains two gratings (1200 gs/mm and 300 gs/mm) that can be interchanged (one grating holder empty).  The whole apparatus is placed on the stabilizer (high performance laminar flow isolator, Newport I-2000 Series). The measurements are controlled by LabView written software (FSC Software Library, copyright: Manfred Heuberger) [2].

properties.INTRODUCTION: The basic principle of the surface force apparatus (SFA) is the measurement of force occurring between two curved surfaces. The surfaces must be cylindrically curved and the cylinder axis are oriented at an angle of 90° to each other.

properties.QUALITY_CONTROL:
avoid the appearance of birefringence; i.e. double peaks of interference spectrum.

no wrinkels and scretches on mica surface should be visible.
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. If there are any samples already inside the eSFA, make sure, that those samples are well separated (e.g. 1-3 mm) from each other using the micrometer on top of the eSFA. Open the thermal insulation box and disconnect the connection between the eSFA unit and the nitrogen (see Fig. 1, marked with black arrow) and the two motor connections (see Fig. 1, marked with red arrow). Move the eSFA unit into a laminar-flow cabinet in order to minimalize the risk of particulate/dust contamination for the eSFA interior as well as the sample during mounting.

2. Release the four screws at the top of the eSFA (see Fig. 2, marked with black arrow) and remove the clamping plate underneath. Take out carefully the cylinder flange that holds the upper surface and place it in the clean laminar-flow near the eSFA unit.

3.Release the four screws at the bottom of the eSFA (see Fig. 2, marked with red arrow) using a short screwdriver (e.g. SwissTools PB 135.3-30) and move carefully the upper chamber of the eSFA onto the specially designed 4-pin holder (see Figure 3, upper unit at position (4)).

4. Clean the eSFA unit with (optionally with clean water, then) Ethanol and blow dry with gentle flow of dry nitrogen. Place the sample into the upper sample holder (see Figure 4). Tight up the three screws at the side of the sample holder using screwdriver (290.110 Qty 1). Don't tight up the screws to much otherwise the silica disc may be damaged. It is important to mind the orientation of the cylinder axis as well as the mica sample orientation. The information about mica orientation should be written in the lab book during cleaving and gluing. The cylinder axis should be oriented such that the lower cylinder axis is parallel to the long axis of the eSFA. Finally, the mica samples should end up in a 90° crossed cylinder geometry. When using two micas with exactly the same thickness, this procedure will readily avoid the appearance of birefringence; i.e. double peaks of interference spectrum.

5. Mount the second sample into the lower sample holder (see Fig. 5). Tight up the one screw using screwdriver (Wiha, 260/ 2,5x50). Place the upper SFA chamber back onto the lower eSFA chamber (same configuration as at the start).

6. Place the cylindrical flange into the eSFA unit with the metal clamping plate and tighten the four screws slightly. These four screws are spring-loaded to reduce the effects of instrumental drift during operation. The cylinder flange sample holder on top can be adjusted in position and rotation relative to the lower mica sample (see also SOP – alignment of the setup). Then the screws will be finally tightened.

7. Place the eSFA unit back into the thermal insulation box. Three structured holes in the eSFA enclosure define the correct position of the SFA unit. Connect the motors and the nitrogen line into the SFA unit. Note that connecting the motors while the PMC motor card is ON may result in motion errors; these can usually be fixed by consecutive forward/backward commands issued by the motor controller software (e.g. 830_eSFA motor module).

Example of the end result of the calibration - sufficient for eSFA measurement

For further information about FECO check: [2] Advanced FECO Topics – Surface Science and Technology | ETH Zurich
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. The screws in the system have following functions (compare Fig. 1):

Figure 1: eSFA unit with marked positions of alignment screws

 

(1) tilting the position on the prism in x-direction (vertical displacement of the PCA image)

(2) moving the gap distance between the two surfaces

(3) moving the prism table (polar coordinate of optics stand)

(4) focus movement of the objective lens (change focus with simultaneous vertical displacement of PCA) 

(5) tilting of the mirror below eSFA unit (optimize illumination and minimize reflections)

(6) rotation of the mirror below the eSFA unit (optimize illumination and minimize reflections)

(7) movement of the mirror in y-direction (optimize illumination and minimize reflections)

(8) rotation of the prism. Open the locking screw and rotate the position of the prism. Tight up the screw when optimal position is reached.

2. Bring the mica surfaces to a visibly small separation <1mm using screw (2).  Manually replace the prism by a monochromatic narrow-band filter and an eyepiece at the top for viewing of Newton rings. To see Newton rings for coarse adjustment, the narrow band pass filter can also be replaced by a monochromatic sodium lamp illumination, which will increase the coherence length. Align the mirror position (screws (5)-(7)) as well as the position of the prism table (screws at the back of the eSFA) in order to place and focus the Newton rings in the center of the field of view (eyepiece). Use the micrometer (2) to further reduce the separation between the surfaces while avoiding direct contact.

3. Clean contact between the surfaces is established when the weak vibrations during the distance approach stopped and the Newton rings are very sharp. Avoid contact as well as pressing on the contact, since this might damage the mica surfaces. Once the contact region look clean and symmetric, tighten the spring-loaded screws holding the cylinder flange sample holder; note that this action may reduce the surface separation and cause unwanted surface contact/loading.

 

4. Remove the bandpass filter and the eyepiece. Place the 90° prism. Use a white paper in front of the spectrometer entrance slit and visualize a bright spot from the contact region with appropriate focusing. With minor refocusing, the FECO should then become visible on the CCD camera image.

5. Once is adjusted near the spectrometer slit entrance, open the LabView VI: ProSilicaGE4000. The continuous run mode gives you the real-time image of the CCD. The intensity of the signal can be changed by varying the slit entrance and/or reducing the exposure time (software: 510_CCD_FSC, for further information check [1]). A typical exposure time is 100-500 ms. Adjust the position of the prism (screw (1) & (2)) as well as the focus (4) of the fringes. Try to get the fringes as sharp and clear as possible.

6. Adjust the spectrometer slit to obtain a maximum of fringe intensity, but avoid reducing the resolution too much so that the fringes are unnecessarily broadened. For eSFA, a typical slit width is 100-200 micrometers.

7.Close the thermal insulation box. The fringes should still be visible on the camera; the light now travels through the window in the box wall. Turn on the temperature controller power controller and the corresponding power supply. Start 440_Temperature software module in order to control and record the temperature inside the thermal box. A typical control temperature is 22°C unless otherwise required. 

8. Once the thermal box is closed, the further alignment steps can take place in an automated fashionvia motor operating software. In general, two motors requires more precise alignment – pseudo motor (vertical PCA axis) and the prism motor (horizontal PCA axis). In order to align them, start the program 510_CCD_FSC and perform drift monitoring as well as 2D/3D PCA alignment scans (see SOP- software).
properties.PRINCIPLE: In following, the main steps of finding the PCA are described, however, every experimentalist may find his/her own optimal way to adjust the setup based on his/her experience with the alignment procedure or possible instrumental modifications.

properties.INTRODUCTION: Once the mica surfaces are mounted (see SOP - sample mounting), the optical path must be aligned in order to detect the interference fringes of equal chromatic order (FECO). In the eSFA the goal of the alignment is to measure interference fringes at the Point of Closest Approach (PCA) between the two crossed cylinder surfaces.

properties.PROCEDURE:
Spectrometer opening/calibration

Light focused at the entrance slit is spatially dispersed by a grating and focused to an image plane outside via a toroidal mirror. The virtual image is then detected by a CCD detector slightly outside the spectrometer. For sporadic maintenance, the spectrometer can be opened on the top. Therefore, you can normally skip points 1-7 of the first SOP below. Opening the spectrometer should be executed in dust-free environment (e.g. laminar flow cabinet) to prevent deterioration of optical surfaces.

  1. Disconnect the spectrometer from the PC and power supply. Release the upper screw in order to unmount the CCD camera adapter. Close the empty CCD adapter opening with a piece of paper in order to avoid dust in the spectrograph.

2. Bring the spectrometer as whole unit to the laminar-flow cabinet, release all the screws at the top and open the spectrometer.

 

Figure 3: Opened spectrometer with visible grating and the two mirrors, during alignment of the central wavelength, the turret is rotating a few degrees (e.g. 3-5°); larger rotations are used to switch between gratings (three grating positions). The toroidal mirrors are seen on the left.

 

Figure 4: Layout of the spectrograph with M1 (M2): mirror 1 (2), G: grating, ES: slit entrance. All distances in mm are measured for our spectrometer in the eSFA laboratory. Schematic adapted from [1].

 

3.Clean the mirrors with a gentle blow of nitrogen. Under no circumstances ever touch the optical surfaces – it can cause scratches.

4.After inspection, close the spectrograph and tighten up all the screws at the top. Replace the piece of paper at the CCD entrance with a reverse-illumination adapter, which allows to attach fiber optical lamp at the center of the exit plane.

 

 

5. Connect the optical fiber lamp (FiberOptic FOT150) and switch it on. Place the fiber inside the adapter (at the position where usually the CCD is). Open the spectrometer slit as required.

6. Place paper screen, optionally with calibration template behind the prism. Adjust the spectrometer position until you see that the outcoming light is centered on the prism. Optionally mark the spectrometer position on its support surface and write down the current date of the calibration.

7. Turn off the optical fiber lamp and remove the reverse-illumination adapter and place instead the CCD camera adapter. Connect the spectrometer to the power supply and to the PC. Make sure that all the electronics and the PC is off, before initialization and re-establishing a connection to the spectrometer.

properties.INTRODUCTION: Several adjustments and calibrations need to be performed before running an eSFA measurement.
properties.PRINCIPLE: In following, the basic adjustments of the setup such spectrometer calibration, adjustment of the CCD, CCD dark current measurement, white light correction, psuedo & prism motor calibration are described.
properties.EQUIPMENT_REAGENTS:
• for basic equipment see SOP - starting eSFA.
  • optical fiber lamp (FiberOptic FOT150) 
  • calibration lamp (Acton Research Corporation Model MS416m SN 416117 (1297), Pwr. 270 V @ 18mA)
  • vertically adjustable laboratory bench (Karl Kurt Juchheim,, DIN 12 897)
  • optical ruler

properties.PROCEDURE:
Adjustment of the CCD

  1. Turn on the PC, initialize the spectrometer and switch ON the calibration lamp (Acton Research Corporation Model MS416m SN 416117 (1297), Pwr. 270 V @ 18mA). Start the program 600_Spectrometer in order to check if the spectrometer is in communication with the PC (optional).
  2. In order to adjust the focus of the CCD camera, start the program 510_CCD. Adjust a very narrow slit opening and set following parameters: exposure: 20, width: 5, level 1, averaging 1. Move the focus wheel at the side of the spectrometer exit adapter in order to adjust the focus. Note that the adapter only moves outwards and requires gentle manual pressure to move inwards. In optimal focus, the calibration appear nearly symmetric and very narrow. An optional marking on the adjusting wheel at the spectrometer helps to find the right position later.
  3. In the next step, switch the working mode of the 510_eSFA_CCD module to "CCD Utility" and press the button "camera tilt". A pop-up window appears which displays the difference between the peak positions at top and bottom of the CCD camera. Manually rotate the CCD camera adapter until you reach a difference in the order or below 10-3pixel. Optimize the parameters – average (3-16) and width (3-5) and check different calibration lines. Tighten the screw above the CCD in order to fix the position of the CCD – verify that this operation did not change the CCD tilt adjustment.
properties.INTRODUCTION: The goal of this adjustment step is to adjust the focus and the tilt angle of the CCD camera.

properties.PROCEDURE:
Every CCD detector creates statistical noise and has a signal offset; this noise is actually individual for each pixel. The CCD noise can be well characterized in complete darkness and during subsequent experiments be removed from the CCD signal. It arises from statistical variation of number of electrons thermally generated within the silicon stricture of the CCD and its amplifier electronics. The rate of generation of the thermal electrons at specific temperature is called dark current [2].  It depends non-linearly on temperature and accumulates linearly with exposure time [3].

  1. Turn off all possible lights in the lab. Darken the entrance slit, for example, with the calibration lamp adapter in OFF mode. Start the program 510_CCD module and switch the working mode from PCA monitor (standard) into CCD Utility.
  2. Press the button "CCD Noise" and start the measurement (compare Fig. 7). The exposure time will be automatically varied and the corresponding dark current is detected. Don't forget to save the calibration into the configuration file by pressing "SAVE" (button placed at the bottom right of the 510_CCD main window).
  3. In order to subtract the dark-current from the performed measurements, the tickbox "background" must be activated at all times (compare Fig. 7, section signal) on the 510_eSFA_CCD module front panel.

 

 

Figure 1: 510_CCD software [4]. Working mode is marked by red rectangle, the CCD noise button for dark current measurement is marked blue. In this case, the background and white light correction is on (compare tickboxes on in section signal).
properties.INTRODUCTION: CCD Dark current measurement

properties.PROCEDURE:
1. First, make sure that there is no mica interferometer inside the eSFA (i.e. no mica samples inside, clean silica discs are fine). Block unwanted lights from the laboratory, e.g. using a piece of dark foam behind the prism. Work with a stabilized illumination lamp.

2. Start the program 510_CCD, turn the tickbox white lamp OFF and adjust the parameters. Find the optimal exposure time (e.g. 200) and set peak detector width (25), average (between 4-16, 8 optimal), level (50) and filter (1). Make sure that the background tickbox ro remove CCD dark noise is ON.

 

 

3. Switch the working mode from PCA monitor (standard) into CCD Utility and press the button "White Light". The software records the transmission function of the system with low noise for later numerical "white light" normalization.

4. Switch back to the PCA monitor and press "SAVE". The white light normalization is completed and can be activated by the tickbox "white light" for following eSFA measurements.
properties.INTRODUCTION: The eSFA measurements are based on white light interferometry. In a real setup, lamps and optical elements never transmit exactly white light, therefore, a white-light normalization can be done numerically. Due to ageing of the lamp and frequent changes in optics paths, it is useful to repeat the white light normalization procedure periodically, say every 100h of lamp life, or, any major change in optical parts.

properties.PROCEDURE:
For the calibration of the pseudo motor a transparent ruler with black markings every 100 μm is used at the exact location where the mica samples are during an eSFA experiment. The calibration is performed by moving the motor manually from the start position to a number of calibration positions of your choice. For each point, it is necessary to enter the real distance travelled on the stage. At the end, the motor automatically move back whereby the maximum velocity is calibrated.

Note1: the "pseudo" motor does not actually move any parts, but depending on its nominal position a particular line of the CCD image is selected for FSC interferometer calculation.

Note 2: Using the modules.ini file, one can also adjust the type of vertical line binning as well as the type of CCD "dark" offset drift correction.

  1. Remove the eSFA unit and place the ruler at the same place and at the same height (use focus) as the mica samples (see Fig. 10). For this purpose use a vertically adjustable laboratory bench (Karl Kurt Juchheim,, DIN 12 897) located in the lab cupboard. Open ProSilicaGE4000_Driver software and focus the 100 μm markings of the ruler (see Fig. 11) by vertical positioning of the optical ruler. 

 

 

2. Start 510_CCD software. Switch the lever switch in the 510_CCD software from "measure" to "adjust". A real-time display of the total CCD intensity will appear.

3. Start 840_Pseudo_Motor software and press the button "Calibrate". Additional calibration window 840_CAL will appear.

4. Follow the instructions in the calibration window 840_CAL. The maximum number of useful calibration points for the pseudo motor is limited to three points (0, 100 μm, 200 μm). Enter this number before the calibration starts (see "distance values" in Fig.12) 

5. Move the motor by using the motion arrows until you see a significant drop in the intensity (i.e. you are at the position of the marking on the ruler). Moving back up with the intensity, adjust the position of the motor until you reach a value of intensity e.g. of 10M (use the same reference point for all positions) and press "proceed". Move to the next point and repeat the procedure until your number of points is reached.

6. At the end, the motor automatically move back and the velocity is calibrated. Press "SAVE" in the calibration window 840_CAL and save .dat file into the 840_CALIBS folder. Close the window and press "SAVE" in the 840_Pseudo_Motor software (check Fig. 12). The pseudo motor calibration is completed.
properties.INTRODUCTION: Pseudo motor calibration

properties.PROCEDURE:
The prism motor calibration proceeds analog to the pseudo motor calibration, except the fact that the ruler may be placed at different angle (90 degrees rotated compared to the position during the pseudo motor calibration, the lines are no longer visible since the entire image is darkened).  The overview of the necessary software is provided in Fig. 1.

  1. Remove the eSFA unit and place the ruler at the same place and at the same height as the mica samples. Open ProSilicaGE4000_Driver and focus on the 100 μm markings of the ruler. Ideally, one can use the same ruler focus position as for the previous "pseudo" motor calibration.
  2. Start 510_CCD software. Switch of the lever in the 510_CCD software from "measure" to "adjust". An intensity display will appear.
  3. Start 833_Prism_Motor software and verify that the physical position of the prizm micrometer is roughly centered. Then press the button "Calibrate". Additional calibration window 833_CAL will appear.
  4. Follow the instructions in the calibration window 833_CAL. The maximum number of points needs to be entered before the calibration starts (see "distance values" in Fig.12); a useful number for the prizm motor is 5 points.
  5. Move the motor by using the motion arrows until you see a significant drop in the intensity (i.e. you are at the position of the marking on the ruler). Going back up with the intensity, adjust the position of the motor until you reach a value of intensity of 10M and press "proceed". Move to the next point and repeat the procedure until your number of points is reached.

       6. At the end, the motor automatically move back and the velocity is calibrated. Press "SAVE" in the calibration window 833_CAL and save .dat file into the 833_CALIBS folder. Close the window and press "SAVE" also in the 833_USER software to update the configuration parameters. The prism motor calibration is completed.
properties.INTRODUCTION: prism motor calibration

properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Place the container in the laminar-flow cabinet in order to avoid contamination. Release the three screws on the top and open the container.
  2. Clean the container with ethanol and dry it with nitrogen. Don`t forget to clean the connection line.
  3. Make sure that the valve (see Fig.1, No.3) below the container is closed. Fill the required liquid into the container. It should be at least half full. Afterwards, close the container (tight up all three screws). Test if the line is working by letting small amount of liquid through the connection line.
  4. Connect the container to the eSFA by replacing the nitrogen line with the liquid line. Open the valve on the top of the container (see Fig. 1, No. 2) and remove the cap from the air filter (see Fig. 1, No. 1) in order to push the liquid through. The eSFA chamber will be filled with liquid. The process can take up to 15 min.
  5. Once the liquid is flowing out from eSFA side valve (No. 4, Fig. 2), close the valves (No.1 & No. 4, Fig. 2).  Wait until the temperature in system stabilize before starting a measurement.

Mounting out

  1. Close the valve No. 2 & No. 3 (Fig. 2) and disconnect the line between the eSFA and the container. Bring the eSFA unit and the container into laminar-flow cabinet. Connect the line to the eSFA unit and let run out the liquid into vessel. Once there is no more liquid in the upper part of the eSFA, you can open the eSFA unit by hand and remove the liquid.
  2.  Clean up the eSFA unit as well as the container with ethanol and dry it with a blow of nitrogen.
properties.INTRODUCTION: Special container is used in order to insert liquids into eSFA.

properties.PROCEDURE:
1. Make sure that intern water supply circle is on (Legrand (UV2) MD01 120F1) and turn on the cooling water flows using the valves at the wall, behind the eSFA table. Doublecheck if the water is flowing by looking at  "water wheels" behind the eSFA.

 

 

Figure 2: eSFA setup at Empa St. Gallen (April 2022) with major components needed for starting the eSFA

 

2. Start the power supply of the arc lamp, Müller Elektronik Optik Type SVX1450, by pressing "NETZ", the red light "START" will come on to indicate sufficient cooling water flow. Then switch on the xenon arc lamp by pressing the red button "START".

3. Turn on the temperature power supply and the temperature controller. Switch on the PCI unit and start the power strip at the table. You should now hear the spectrometer initialization sounds (variation in grating position).

4. Turn on the PC. Log-in into the account (402, Labor Ruby - password protected) and start the following programs placed on the desktop: 440_Temperature & 510_CCD.
properties.PRINCIPLE:
Common sample surfaces are 2-10 µm thick, manually cleaved mica substrates (see MICASOP01 - cutting & cleaving) with nominally 40 nm-thick evaporated silver layer on the outer faces (see SOP_mica_preperation_silvering). By moving the motor by the amount M, the distance D between the surfaces can be varied. One of the surface is mounted on a compliant spring with spring constant k. During the experiment, the distance D as a function of the actuator is optically measured (using Multiple Beam Interferometry), thus allowing to calculate the sum surface force, F=k(M-D).

The traditionally used SFAs are based on the acquisition of a single fringe wavelength, thus resulting in a distance resolution of ≈100-300 pm [1]. Considering the acquisition of multiple fringe wavelengths and the evaluation for interference spectra using spectral correlation interferometry, the precision of distance measurement can be around 20 pm. Based on this improvements, the instrument is called then extended surface forces apparatus (eSFA).
properties.EQUIPMENT_REAGENTS:
Figure 1: Schematic of the eSFA setup.

The extended Surface Force Apparatus (eSFA) consists of an automated version of the SFA3TM (1997, Surforce, USA). The instrument is placed in an own-build insulated enclosure, providing stable thermal conditions ±20mK after a few hours equilibration. The temperature is controlled by EUROTHERM 2216e controller, powered by external power supply EA-PS-7032-10 A. Several encoded DC motors are inside the enclosure in order to make optical adjustments of the setup and changing the distance between the two surfaces. The movement of the motors is controlled by a PMC controller card inside an EXSYS EX-1031 4x PCI Expansion Box. The motors are individually connected to a separate pinout box via D-sub connectors.

The light is provided by a Xenon Short arc lamp with 450 W (SN: EQRKF i548), powered by xenon lamp power supply Müller Elektronik Optik Type SVX1450. The white light is directed into the eSFA housing via two dichroic mirrors in series; this minimizes the IR heating of the experiment. The outcoming light is collected by imaging lens and directed into the spectrograph (Acton Research Corporation Spectra Pro-500i, 0.5 Meter Triple Grating Monochromator), where the spectra are detected by a high-resolution CCD camera Allied Vision Technologies (GigE 4000, 4008x2672 pixels).  The spectrometer contains two gratings (1200 gs/mm and 300 gs/mm) that can be interchanged (one grating holder empty).  The whole apparatus is placed on the stabilizer (high performance laminar flow isolator, Newport I-2000 Series). The measurements are controlled by LabView written software (FSC Software Library, copyright: Manfred Heuberger) [2].

properties.INTRODUCTION: The basic principle of the surface force apparatus (SFA) is the measurement of force occurring between two curved surfaces. The surfaces must be cylindrically curved and the cylinder axis are oriented at an angle of 90° to each other.

properties.QUALITY_CONTROL:
avoid the appearance of birefringence; i.e. double peaks of interference spectrum.

no wrinkels and scretches on mica surface should be visible.
properties.PROCEDURE:
1. If there are any samples already inside the eSFA, make sure, that those samples are well separated (e.g. 1-3 mm) from each other using the micrometer on top of the eSFA. Open the thermal insulation box and disconnect the connection between the eSFA unit and the nitrogen (see Fig. 1, marked with black arrow) and the two motor connections (see Fig. 1, marked with red arrow). Move the eSFA unit into a laminar-flow cabinet in order to minimalize the risk of particulate/dust contamination for the eSFA interior as well as the sample during mounting.

2. Release the four screws at the top of the eSFA (see Fig. 2, marked with black arrow) and remove the clamping plate underneath. Take out carefully the cylinder flange that holds the upper surface and place it in the clean laminar-flow near the eSFA unit.

3.Release the four screws at the bottom of the eSFA (see Fig. 2, marked with red arrow) using a short screwdriver (e.g. SwissTools PB 135.3-30) and move carefully the upper chamber of the eSFA onto the specially designed 4-pin holder (see Figure 3, upper unit at position (4)).

4. Clean the eSFA unit with (optionally with clean water, then) Ethanol and blow dry with gentle flow of dry nitrogen. Place the sample into the upper sample holder (see Figure 4). Tight up the three screws at the side of the sample holder using screwdriver (290.110 Qty 1). Don't tight up the screws to much otherwise the silica disc may be damaged. It is important to mind the orientation of the cylinder axis as well as the mica sample orientation. The information about mica orientation should be written in the lab book during cleaving and gluing. The cylinder axis should be oriented such that the lower cylinder axis is parallel to the long axis of the eSFA. Finally, the mica samples should end up in a 90° crossed cylinder geometry. When using two micas with exactly the same thickness, this procedure will readily avoid the appearance of birefringence; i.e. double peaks of interference spectrum.

5. Mount the second sample into the lower sample holder (see Fig. 5). Tight up the one screw using screwdriver (Wiha, 260/ 2,5x50). Place the upper SFA chamber back onto the lower eSFA chamber (same configuration as at the start).

6. Place the cylindrical flange into the eSFA unit with the metal clamping plate and tighten the four screws slightly. These four screws are spring-loaded to reduce the effects of instrumental drift during operation. The cylinder flange sample holder on top can be adjusted in position and rotation relative to the lower mica sample (see also SOP – alignment of the setup). Then the screws will be finally tightened.

7. Place the eSFA unit back into the thermal insulation box. Three structured holes in the eSFA enclosure define the correct position of the SFA unit. Connect the motors and the nitrogen line into the SFA unit. Note that connecting the motors while the PMC motor card is ON may result in motion errors; these can usually be fixed by consecutive forward/backward commands issued by the motor controller software (e.g. 830_eSFA motor module).

The intensity of the signal can be changed by varying the slit entrance and/or reducing the exposure time (software: 510_CCD_FSC, for further information check [1]). A typical exposure time is 100-500 ms. Adjust the position of the prism (screw (1) & (2)) as well as the focus (4) of the fringes. Try to get the fringes as sharp and clear as possible.

6. Adjust the spectrometer slit to obtain a maximum of fringe intensity, but avoid reducing the resolution too much so that the fringes are unnecessarily broadened. For eSFA, a typical slit width is 100-200 micrometers.

7.Close the thermal insulation box. The fringes should still be visible on the camera; the light now travels through the window in the box wall. Turn on the temperature controller power controller and the corresponding power supply. Start 440_Temperature software module in order to control and record the temperature inside the thermal box. A typical control temperature is 22°C unless otherwise required. 

8. Once the thermal box is closed, the further alignment steps can take place in an automated fashionvia motor operating software. In general, two motors requires more precise alignment – pseudo motor (vertical PCA axis) and the prism motor (horizontal PCA axis). In order to align them, start the program 510_CCD_FSC and perform drift monitoring as well as 2D/3D PCA alignment scans (see SOP- software).

properties.INTRODUCTION: Once the mica surfaces are mounted (see SOP - sample mounting), the optical path must be aligned in order to detect the interference fringes of equal chromatic order (FECO). In the eSFA the goal of the alignment is to measure interference fringes at the Point of Closest Approach (PCA) between the two crossed cylinder surfaces.

properties.PROCEDURE:
Spectrometer opening/calibration

Light focused at the entrance slit is spatially dispersed by a grating and focused to an image plane outside via a toroidal mirror. The virtual image is then detected by a CCD detector slightly outside the spectrometer. For sporadic maintenance, the spectrometer can be opened on the top. Therefore, you can normally skip points 1-7 of the first SOP below. Opening the spectrometer should be executed in dust-free environment (e.g. laminar flow cabinet) to prevent deterioration of optical surfaces.

  1. Disconnect the spectrometer from the PC and power supply. Release the upper screw in order to unmount the CCD camera adapter. Close the empty CCD adapter opening with a piece of paper in order to avoid dust in the spectrograph.

2. Bring the spectrometer as whole unit to the laminar-flow cabinet, release all the screws at the top and open the spectrometer.

 

Figure 3: Opened spectrometer with visible grating and the two mirrors, during alignment of the central wavelength, the turret is rotating a few degrees (e.g. 3-5°); larger rotations are used to switch between gratings (three grating positions). The toroidal mirrors are seen on the left.

 

Figure 4: Layout of the spectrograph with M1 (M2): mirror 1 (2), G: grating, ES: slit entrance. All distances in mm are measured for our spectrometer in the eSFA laboratory. Schematic adapted from [1].

 

3.Clean the mirrors with a gentle blow of nitrogen. Under no circumstances ever touch the optical surfaces – it can cause scratches.

4.After inspection, close the spectrograph and tighten up all the screws at the top. Replace the piece of paper at the CCD entrance with a reverse-illumination adapter, which allows to attach fiber optical lamp at the center of the exit plane.

 

 

5. Connect the optical fiber lamp (FiberOptic FOT150) and switch it on. Place the fiber inside the adapter (at the position where usually the CCD is). Open the spectrometer slit as required.

6. Place paper screen, optionally with calibration template behind the prism. Adjust the spectrometer position until you see that the outcoming light is centered on the prism. Optionally mark the spectrometer position on its support surface and write down the current date of the calibration.

7. Turn off the optical fiber lamp and remove the reverse-illumination adapter and place instead the CCD camera adapter. Connect the spectrometer to the power supply and to the PC. Make sure that all the electronics and the PC is off, before initialization and re-establishing a connection to the spectrometer.
